A number of prominent Russians are echoing a chorus of global celebrities condemning Moscow’s war on Ukraine, with some already beginning to suffer the consequences for defying the Kremlin line. When Russia annexed the Ukrainian Black Sea peninsula of Crimea in 2014, hundreds of artists signed a petition organized by the ministry of culture to back the move. But this time, the consensus appears shakier: Since President Vladimir Putin launched a war on Ukraine, big Russian cities have, unusually, become the scene of rare protests and police retaliating with mass arrests. UK Bans Russian Airlines From Entering British Airspace, Russia… Joe Biden To Nominate Ketanji Brown Jackson For US Supreme Court “Fear and pain. No to war,” wrote Ivan Urgant, the usually smiley king of the late-night TV chat shows in Russia on Instagram with an all-black picture. Russia’s most popular rapper Oxxxymiron, in an angry video message released on his social media accounts, declared he was “against this war that Russia is unleashing against Ukraine”. “I think it is a catastrophe and a crime,” he said as he strode through his home city of Saint Petersburg.